{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/a-paperless-holiday-2b59b0b98b1f", "time": 1683002470.9777548, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/a-paperless-holiday-2b59b0b98b1f/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "A Paperless Holiday. Send greeting cards using Python | by Chubing Tripepi | Towards Data Science", "h1": "A Paperless Holiday", "description": "The holiday season is warm and loving, but it might also mean a lot of waste is generated from the wrapping paper, greeting cards and envelopes, etc. One solution to mitigate this problem is to send\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://lbre.stanford.edu/pssistanford-recycling/frequently-asked-questions/frequently-asked-questions-holiday-waste-prevention", "anchor_text": "Stanford University", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://myaccount.google.com/lesssecureapps", "anchor_text": "Allow less secure apps", "paragraph_index": 6}], "all_paragraphs": ["The holiday season is warm and loving, but it might also mean a lot of waste is generated from the wrapping paper, greeting cards and envelopes, etc.", "\u201cAmericans throw away 25% more trash during the Thanksgiving to New Year\u2019s holiday period than any other time of year. The extra waste amounts to 25 million tons of garbage, or about 1 million extra tons per week\u201d. \u2014 Stanford University", "One solution to mitigate this problem is to send e-greeting cards instead of paper cards. It will save unnecessary paper waste and money. This year, with Python\u2019s help, we were able to send greeting cards to over 100 family members and friends globally with personalized messages and produced zero paper waste.", "To manage the contacts, you can use Excel or Google Sheet, whatever is easier for you. Mine just has three columns, \u201cEmail\u201d, \u201cGreeting\u201d, and \u201cMessage\u201d. The Email column contains the email address for the recipients. The Greeting column is how you would like to greet them, and lastly, the Message column can contain any personalized message if you\u2019d like to. If not, simply leave it blank.", "As for creating the Christmas card, there are many apps available which will help you to make your own. This year I made ours by using an iPhone app called \u201cInstaMag.\u201d", "Now that we have the contact information and Christmas card, we can load them into Python. Make sure you save the files in the same folder with the code.", "We will use SMTP server to connect to your email server. Please note that if you have Gmail, you will need to set Allow less secure apps to ON, which might cause security issues and make it easier for others to gain access to your Gmail account. Some suggested opening a new Gmail account for Python only for security reasons, but for me, I just used my outlook account this time since I don\u2019t use it for anything important. Another option would be to turn the setting ON while you send the e-cards, and then turn it back OFF again when you\u2019re done.", "With the contact information from the Excel file, we can loop through the email address rows provided. If there\u2019s no personalized message provided, the email body will be \u201cMerry Christmas and Happy New Year!\u201d. If there is a personalized message in the spreadsheet, then it will be placed in the body instead. Once we\u2019ve attached the body and the Christmas card to the message, we can send the email.", "Hope you find this post useful. Happy holidays!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Senior Analytics Engineer @Spotify | RYT\u00ae 200 Yoga Instructor | PADI Open Water Diver | Surfrider Foundation Supporter & Volunteer | Puzzle Solver"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F2b59b0b98b1f&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://m